Our 1st Christmas as a family 🎄❤️🎁👩🏻‍❤️‍👨🏼

Love our Christmas tree from @merryxmastree_th 😍

Time for my 2022 year review! I wrote a blog post about it all (LINK IN BIO), but it was a wild year:

💴 Over $500k generated (read the blog post on how)

✈️ 15 countries: Thailand, UK, France, Italy, Vatican, USA, Cyprus, South Sudan, Central African Republic, Ethiopia, Germany, United Arab Emirates, Mauritania, Morocco

🏠 Finished building my house, bought another investment condo

❎ Failed at least one of my goals 😭

🏔️ Summited one of the 7 summits 

And a lot more of ups, downs, anxiety and stress! More info in the blog post 🙏🏼

Make 2023 yours. You have a whole year to do something amazing. Use it.

I’ve just blogged my 2023 plans (LINK IN BIO). This pic? Mount Everest. 100 days until I start my Everest expedition with @furtenbachadventures 🏔️ I’ve been a bit quiet in the blog and social media front, in full training mode at the moment 🙏🏼💪🏻

Walking into my next Mauritania tour like….

One of the least visited countries in the world, and home to the coolest, adventurous and dirtiest travel ‘experience’ - hitching a ride on the iron ore train, all night through, through the depths of the Sahara ❤️🇲🇷

Can’t wait for the next 10 days! I’m coming back in November for another group tour, they always sell out so if you wanna come ride with me, move fast!🚂 🐫 🏜️

Mauritania ❤️🇲🇷

We are half way through my most recent blog group trip in Mauritania. This country is 🤌

That means the main event, hitching a ride on the iron ore train through the Sahara, is tomorrow!

Wish us luck 😬😬

Hitching a ride on the iron ore train in Mauritania is one of THE coolest travel experiences in the world 🇲🇷🇲🇷

I feel blessed to be able to share this with you guys! My next trip to do this is in November.. check the link in my bio to join me 🚂🚂

Time for an adventure of a lifetime anyone? I'm going out of my mind training for Everest, so I've decided to do a couple of cool trips this year to make my year a little more fun! 

Now... 

Anyone fancy cycling 100km across Jordan for Charity with me and my mum?

Or... visiting Lebanon and Iraq for 5 days (Beirut, Baghdad and Babylon)?

Chartering our own plane and visiting Timbuktu in Mali?

And of course, riding the epic iron ore train in Mauritania?

I'm going to be launching all 4 next weeks, so get ready! They'll sell out pretty fast, normally the same day, so this is the warning post! 

PROVISIONAL DATES:

Jordan: September 27-October 6th. 
= My mum and I will be traveling to jordan, 14 spots available. Meet in Amman, visit the Dead Sea and Petra then we will all CYCLE the 100km across the desert to Wadi Rum (home of Lawrence of Arabia), then go celebrate on the Red Sea, in Aqaba. This will all be fund-raising for Cure Parkinson's. 

Lebanon and Iraq:14-19 October. 
= Meet in Beirut. Couple of days there, then fly to Baghdad and see what's going on there these days, as well as trips to Babylon (home of the Hanging Gardens, the ancient world wonder) and maybe even a visit to Sadam Hussein's palace and check out his hottub. 

Mali, including Timbuktu: NO PUBLIC DATES. 
= If you're interested, DM or email me. For security, no information will be published online. Only 14 spots on the plane available. 

Mauritania, and the Iron Ore train: Nov 26 to Dec 3
= I'm back baby! Coolest adventure in the travel world, 3 spots left. 

Oh, and I'm creating a yearly event in Mauritania where we run 150km (almost 100 miles) over 3 days. From the Eye of the Sahara to the nearest output. If you wanna make your future grandkids proud, join me. Cost price as it's the first year. 20 spots only because I don't wanna anyone to die in the first year! It's December 4-13.

PRICES AND ITINERARIES ARE ALL DONE, JUST MAKING THEM PRETTY AND ANNOUNCING THEM NEXT WEEK, STAYED TUNED!

PS. Turkmenistan, Socotra and Syria in the works too!

I'm about to launch my Jordan trip, complete with a 100km charity cycle, that I'll be doing with my mum in September. 

Hope you guys can come and join me!

Before I launch though, here's my mum's last fundraising effort. 12 years with Parkinson's, 72 years old, doing a 10km as part of the Serengeti Marathon. 

I hope this helps inspire you guys to join us in September. Let's raise another $20k to fight Parkinson's Disease.

The blog link to the article about our experience in the Serengeti marathon is in my bio 🙏🏼

Our Jordan charity 100km cycle trip is now LIVE! Come and join us. We are raising $20k for Cure Parkinson’s, and we’re also going to have a bit of an adventure whilst doing it.

This photo is Wadi Rum, this is where we will finish our 100km cycle. 

The trip is for all ages and abilities, my 74yo mum is doing it! So join us this September/October. Link with all the info is in my bio ❤️🇯🇴

Aaaand Jordan is sold out!  That was fast! 

Either you guys really wanna cycle 100km in the desert, or you wanna see me and my mum suffer 😂 

Or maybe it’s just the prospect of those post-cycle celebrations 🍻 🍾🎉

If you wanna join the waiting list, please go ahead. Orrrr, get ready for the launch of my next trips later in the year:

Mali
Iraq
Turkmenistan
Mauritania 150km ultra marathon

Watch this space 🤜🏻🤛🏻

We’ve been on the Thai-Myanmar border the last few days, helping out a Burmese migrant community with some new dormitories through my @muditaadventures non-profit🙏🏼

We’ve done around 20 projects now and it’s our first one or 2023. This time we had a great partner from Australia, @liquid_learning , who asked if they could help out 3 years ago. Then Covid struck but they stuck to their word and funded the project regardless. Respect 🤜🏻🤛🏻 Finally, they can come and see how the community lives have been improved ❤️

Our partner school houses over 100 migrant workers and Burmese refugees from the Karen community. Forced to flea Myanmar, they’re essentially stateless in Thailand. No education, no funding, no ID. Some of the kids are orphans, many have their parents working away, so the school houses, deeds and teaches them. With no government help. 

Previously, the 20 girls had been sleeping in a bamboo shack, thanks to the Australian team and our team in the ground here in Thailand, the girls are now sleeping in proper bunk beds, with mattresses, a watertight roof and electricity. 

Thanks everyone for their hard work. To the Aussies, to my partner Josh, to David our superstar project coordinator and a big shout out to Woody, Kahn and Taylor. Most companies don’t reach out to do some good, we appreciate you guys 💪🏻💪🏻

Anyone fancy an October city break to Iraq (Baghdad and Babylon)? Because I'm going back there, and you guys are invited!

4 days in Iraq, October 14-17. 

If there are any travel legends out there who wanna do a slightly different trip to your Mexicos or Bali, then hit me up. 16 spots, 6 gone already to friends of mine (and probably another 4 about to go!), so 6-10 spots left!

All the info about itinerary, prices, flights, visas etc is in the link in my BIO section so check out the link 🙂 

But yeah, Baghdad this October? See you there!

PS Is it safe? It's safe enough that I brought my mum on the last trip I ran there, that should be the answer you're looking for!

Turkmenistan (can you spot me?!). Home to the Gates of Hell and possibly the LAST country in the world to open since Covid is FINALLY opening next month. 

So I'm going! And i'm bring 20 odd people with me. 

Unfortunately, it sold out within 90 minutes of publishing the blog post! But if you want to come, please add yourself to the waiting list, I'm going to run another one ASAP!

social_posts.post_text: Starting my Everest expedition tomorrow. 2 months up and down the mountain. Stressed, nervous and scared of failing! Thankfully I’m with the mountains most successful operator @furtenbachadventures , but still it’s a big undertaking. Thanks for all the support. Hopefully I’ll have sporadic internet and can keep you guys all the loop ❤️🏔️🇳🇵

Everest bound… The team for the next couple of months ❤️🇳🇵🏔️

Leaving the comfort, and safety, of Kathmandu for the beauty and suffering of Mount Everest. As ready as we’ll ever be. Let’s do it 🙏🏼💪🏻

We’re in good hands with @furtenbachadventures and @luckydavewatson 🤜🏻🤛🏻

Day 4/50. Phak Ding to Namche Bazaar on my classic Everest climb. 

Hot and sweaty up hill day but gorgeous views of the mountains. Pangs of nerves and realisation punctuate my day with what lies ahead. 

I know I should stay in the present but it’s against my nature. My eyes are on the prize, for better or worse. 🇳🇵🇰🇭

Day 5. 10% of the expedition done. Albeit the easiest 10% 😂😂

Active rest day today on our @furtenbachadventures Everest climb. Lovely walk up to 3900m for our first views of Everest! @luckydavewatson is slowly working on me to learn to appreciate the journey rather than summit (it’s a work in progress but I’m trying!). 

Team is bonding well and things are feeling good. Time to move onwards and upwards tomorrow AM. ❤️🇳🇵

Day 6. Everest climb with @furtenbachadventures 

Namche Bazaar to Phortse. Currently now at around 3900m. Lovely day today. 4/5 hours walking and all still good. Had lunch at a banging spot but had a rude awakening when the sun hid behind the clouds and the temp dropped heavy! It’s gonna be coooold when we get up high 🥶🥶

One night here then further up tomorrow. We have a few nights until we try to tag a 6100m peak, Lobuche, before we settle into base camp for a month. Things slowly getting real 🇳🇵🇳🇵

Day 11. Reality check.

Today we made our way to Lobuche, en route is a huge plateau which serves as a memorial to our fellow climbers and Sherpas who has lost their lives in the Himalayas. Many younger than me, and many as recently as this year. A somber thought. 

With that in mind, I’d love you all to check our @thejuniperfund . This amazing NGO supports the families of local Nepalis and Sherpas of have lost their lives on this he mountain. The work they do is amazing, and represents the true heroes of the Himalayas ❤️🇳🇵

@furtenbachadventures

Day 11. First proper rest day on our Everest climb. 

Tomorrow we start a warm up climb to Lobuche east peak at 6110m or so (20000 feet) so today we got reacquainted with our harness and did some rope with with @luckydavewatson 

Rollercoaster of emotions. Had my first banging headache from altitude last night, instant panic attack 😂 

Feel a lot better today thankfully, and looking forward to getting back on a proper mountain tomorrow 🇳🇵🗻

Our @furtenbachadventures still charging on 💪🏻💪🏻

Everest base camp jn 4 or 5 days, really looking forward to settling in ❤️

2 weeks into our Everest expedition and sh*t is starting to get real.

We finally ventured off the lovely Everest Base Camp trek to tag a 6100m (20,000 feet) Himalayan summit, Lobuche. For our Everest climb, this is simply a warm up. For me personally, it’s the 3rd highest mountain I’ve ever climbed! Very grateful for @luckydavewatson guiding our crew. It’s been a brilliant 3 days, challenging but brilliant.

Climbing Lobuche is a privilege and makes me so confident I choose the right operator in @furtenbachadventures. Climbing it alone can cost $3k to $4k, but these guys add it to the expedition to avoid another rotation through the dangerous (and sometimes deadly) Khumbu icefall.

The team is going strong. We’ve all trained hard, dedicated the best part of the last year of our lives to this expedition. Tomorrow we finally reach base camp ❤️🇳🇵🗻

Day 15 on our @furtenbachadventures Everest climb and feeling truly grateful ❤️🇳🇵

We trekked from Lobuche to Everest Base Camp, and from here the climb truly begins.

I had 3 beers last night, maybe it was the altitude but the hike today was a tad tougher 😂

It’s at base camp that we say goodbye to the tourists and hello to our new home for a month as we go up and down the mountain, through the Khumbu icefall, acclimatise, and then eventually, hit out summit attempt 🤞☘️🗻

I CANNOT WAIT TO SHARE THE @furtenbachadventures BASE CAMP SET-UP! Possibly the best basecamp in the world - ill show you guys tomorrow. Stay tuned! 🇳🇵🇳🇵

Chilly evenings 🥶🥶 Training for Everest while living in Thailand perhaps wasn’t the smartest logistical decision I’ve made in a while 🇹🇭🇳🇵 😂🥶

Our base camp is epic, but the temperatures aren’t always playing on our team! It touched -15 last night! ❄️☃️

Check out my Insta stories from yesterday to se our @furtenbachadventures base camp though. Wild! ❤️😍🇳🇵

Thanks for the hat @jajaaward ❤️

Everest high camps are almost ready. 1 month from now we’ll know if we made it or not.

Ice climbing and rope work with the mountain-man himself @luckydavewatson. Progress every single day 🇳🇵🗻

That’s Everest hiding in the background, the darker kinda-grey peak behind the snowy one. After weeks and months of nerves I feel ready. Confident and keen to try my best.

Were hoping to take on the infamous Khumbu ice fall tomorrow night as we make our way to Camp 1 and Camp 2, but it’s weather dependent. 

6 days at our @furtenbachadventures base camp has our acclimatisation going well, and @luckydavewatson has us all feeling like we can do it. The mental game is such a big part of these huge undertakings and it feels like we are in a good place. We’ll know what’s up in the next 4 weeks, one way or another ❤️🇳🇵🤞🗻
See you guys on the other side ❤️🇳🇵🗻

The last 6 days on Everest have been 🤯

We spent night 1 climbing through the Khumbu Icefall. What an experience. Then a couple of nights at Everest Camp 1, 3 nights at Camp 2 with a day up to (almost) Camp 3.

Hard work at times, super beautiful, great training and our bodies are as ready as they’ll ever be for our Everest summit push.

Our team of 4 climbers on our @furtenbachadventures Everest team, our superstar guide @luckydavewatson, and the whole operation of Sherpa, Porters, cooks and everyone else has put us in a great position to try to get this thing done.

After nearly a week up high we are now recovering at base camp. We’ll recharge and wait for a weather window then head back up with only the summit in mind ❤️🇳🇵🗻

Crossing the ladder bridges in the Khumbu Icefall 😬❄️❤️

📸 @luckydavewatson

Making ourselves at home. I have trained for 9 months, acclimated for 2 months, been on the expedition for 5 weeks, done our rotations, experienced the Khumbu icefall and now we are making Everest Base camp home. 

The weather isn’t playing ball, so we are holding tight and waiting for a window to start the summit push. When we start, it’ll be almost a week. But nothing is looking likely for at least another 5/6/7 days. So we wait. Patience isn’t my strong suit but I’m trying my best.

With @furtenbachadventures we have the best base camp on the mountain, when we push we have the best oxygen in the business, we are where we are supposed to be. Hopefully 2 weeks from now we’ll be successfully  and safe. Preferably drunk in some dive bar in Kathmandu!

📸 @luckydavewatson
null

Rumours about a summit window a week-to-10-days from now got me feeling nervous, excited, ready, scared, motivated. Waiting for news from our @furtenbachadventures team before we know more. 🤞🤞🤞

True to form I tweaked a muscle in my back yesterday too, great timing 👀😂. Sprinting in the cold last night between the communal tent and my tent, I can’t do an expedition without getting injured 😬😬 rest, rest, rest until we go johnny boy.

It’s time to take on Mount Everest. A lifetime dream, a year of sacrifice, training, saving and visualising. 

The actual act is daunting, but the true task was formed the day I committed to this thing. So here I am. Dream big. 

Thanks for all the support. All being well ill be back in a week. ❤️🇳🇵

You can check our progress in @furtenbachadventures instagram. See you on the other side team. ❤️

Mount Everest Summit, 8848m, May 17th, 2023.

Honestly it’s a lot to process amidst the effort, the tears, the pride and the gratitude. 

Before to thank a few people, one thing I want to touch on briefly is the tough job single mothers have in our world. Kid growing up without fathers, mothers struggling day to day to keep the lights on. 

Thank you for what you do. Don’t give up on the kid. Don’t let the kid use it as an excuse to limit themselves. Through love and emotional support, the sky is the limit. Maybe even 8848 metres of it ❤️🗻

Prepare to be bombarded with Everest content over the next week or so, sorry!

But a massive thanks to my mum, my wife and my friendship group. And also to @lukasfurtenbach for believing I could do this. 

If you read my blog, @furtenbachadventures proudly promote their 100% success rate, and here I am, living proof of it. Thank you mate.

I have more emotional@photos and videos to share but I’ve just got down the mountain so this will have to do.

Love you all,

Johnny ❤️🇳🇵🗻

I’ve been an emotional wreck all week, please indulge me for 1 minute.

My Everest summit is dedicated to 2 groups of people. Bear with me. I tried to touch on it last week but I was so tired at the summit, my mumblings missed the mark and failed to do it justice, so let me try again, having had days to reflect on an emotional journey.

Growing up in a single-mother household, 10 years on welfare, was tough. 

Being a young boy without a father is possibly even tougher. One day I’ll tell my story, with my mum’s permission, about my father but at this point let me just say he was a pretty bad guy. But that reality doesn’t determine my future. 

So here we are, top of the world, Everest summit. 

So I really want to dedicate this climb, the summit, and this journey to 2 sets of people who have it really tough. Single mums who are struggling to stay afloat, to pay the bills, to have no one to turn to when times are difficult AND to the boys growing up with no fathers, no one teaching them how to stand up tall, kick a football or shave their beard. It’s really hard. I know it. 100%. It’s so difficult. 

But with the support of each other, with the single parents allowing their kids to dream, in fact forcing them to dream outside of their current circumstances, to know that anything is possible, that there is a light at the end of the tunnel. Don’t give up. When times are difficult, know that you can come out the other side. You’re not limited by your set-up.

So to the mums, thank you for everything you do for us. It’s a thankless task, but with your hard work and dedication, with your selflessness, it allows us to go on to bigger things. Thank you.

And to the sons without fathers, your genetics don’t define you. You can write your own story. You can be who you want to be. Don’t allow yourself to be a victim, easy excuses are a road to no town. Dream big. Life is out there for us, and you can do anything you set your mind to.

And to my mum, all this is dedicated to you. Thank you mum. You’re the most selfless person I’ve ever met. All my successes are down to you. I love you ❤️

A dream without a plan is just a wish. 

In life, you have to take action if you want to achieve anything. Climbing Everest, or running marathons at the North Pole, seem impressive to you guys. I know that. And for sure they are tough experiences, but the actual achievement came from the day I committed to the expeditions. That was the key. 

After the commitment, the training and the expeditions come naturally. Taking action and committing was the real step forward. It's too easy in the modern world to wait around and hope for things to happen. 

So please don't wait around. Life comes and goes fast. Go make yourself proud. Commit to something difficult. Dream big. 

On that note, I've now signed up for my last of my 7 summits. Mount Vinson, the highest mountain in Antarctica. I'll be flying to the South Pole to celebrate after. 

And with that, all being well, I'll be the only person ever to truly visit every country, reach both poles and climb the real 7 summits.

What’s your Everest?

We dream too small. Know that with sacrifice and commitment, you can do pretty much anything that you see someone else do. Make money online, live your dream life, visit every country, climb the highest mountains. But you have to start. And you should start today. 

Someone asked me “What’s your Everest” in 2017. And my answer was Everest. Obviously. To reach that goal, physically, mentally and financially took me 6 years. Nothing worth having comes easy. Suffering and sacrifice are often the most beautiful part of the journey. So stop waiting around for life to be cool. Choose your Everest. Go out and suffer, and sacrifice. Make a true commitment to a huge goal. 

And then let’s go get party in Thailand to celebrate. See you there, 6 years from now 🍾🥂🇹🇭

2 weeks on from my expedition, I’m still in recovery mode. Time to go chill. A week of relaxing in the Bahamas is due. 

First stop, city break in Stockholm, then straight to the Exhumas, 5 nights at @embracestanielcay to swim with the pigs and tick off a bucket list item!A world away from suffering at 8000m is what the doctor (and my wife!) ordered 🇧🇸🐷
@3nsstanielcay

Stockholm Syndrome 🇸🇪

City break in Sweden’s capital before hitting the Bahamas.

Tips for Stockholm city break:
1) Airport bus is $20 cheaper than airport train!

2) Check out @meatballsforthepeople for your first Swedish meal 🤤

3) Coffee and kanelbullar at Cafe and Bageri Pascal

4) Walk to Monteliusvägen viewpoint

5) then walk for a beer at Stortorget square in Gamlastan

- all doable by foot (15-20k steps), great first day. For dinner we’re going to picnic at one of the parks in Sodermalm. Cheap, lovely, and outdoors ❤️🇸🇪

1 month ago I stood atop of Mount Everest. Celebrating in the Bahamas and drove across the island to the north of Staniel Cay in the Bahamas. Feels like another planet from cold and wind of Everest ❤️🇧🇸

Staniel Cay is the best hop off point to go and swim with the pigs in the Exhumas, so I never expected to find untouched beaches like this 😍😍

Thanks to Natajia from @embracestanielcay and @3nsstanielcay for the recommendation!

I had never heard of Staniel Cay until swimming with the pigs became famous, but better late than never 🐷🇧🇸

Once I knew my Everest expedition dates, I organised 4 nights at @embracestanielcay on the island and a trip to see the pigs with @3nsstanielcay but I wasn’t expecting this place to be so beautiful!

It’s true Caribbean style, no big resorts, just chill vibes and the best beach I’ve ever seen in my life. Now we have the pigs tomorrow for our last day, one final bucket list before we leave ✌️🤞

Swimming with pigs in the Bahamas ❤️🐷🇧🇸

🏝️ WHERE? The original pig beach is next to Staniel Cay, in the Bahamas. We stayed at @embracestanielcay. Far and away the best value place on the island.

✈️ HOW? You can fly direct to Bahamas from the US, London, Paris etc. Easy! Then you can take a loooong (and expensive) day trip from there. Or, better, take a 30 min, $100 flight and stay in paradise on Staniel Cay. You can do a half day trip from here!

💰 PRICE? from here, $300. From Nassau, $675. Not cheap but amazing!

🐷 EXPERIENCE? One of the best holiday day-trips of my life! We booked through @3nsstanielcay. I was expecting it to be super busy, and overly touristic but it didn’t feel like that at all tbh. You also get to check out sharks, sand bars, cave swimming. Insane day. 

🪣 BUCKET LIST? ✔️❤️

I wanted to gift Jaa a bucket list for our first wedding anniversary, so last December 18th (our anniversary) I surprised her with this! But I didn’t wanna drink a million beers and get fat until AFTER Everest so we delayed the trip until now. And finally we did it. WHAT A DAY ❤️🙏🏼❤️🐷🇧🇸

NEW TURKMENISTAN TOUR… November 19-24 2023. 

11 spots gone, 5 spots left. It’s gonna sell out! Check the info in the link in my bio and DM me if you wanna join.

🌆 Ashgabat tour
👹Camping at the Gates of Hell
🚂 Epic night train across the country to the Caspian Sea 
⛰️ Yangy Kala canyon

One of the least visited countries in the world, and rumours of them sealing the gates of hell are rife! So come visit before they close it forever 😱

Day trip in Iceland 🇮🇸🇮🇸

Kerid crater
Gulfoss Falls 
The North and South American continent divide 

Cool day with @getyourguide @getyourguidecommunity

Iceland ❤️🇮🇸

Often renting a car is the best way to see Iceland but it’s very possible to see all the highlights without it. And thats what Jaa and I did.

You can see the main attractions in 2 day trips using Reykjavik as your base, and then one half day to Blue Lagoon too.

For our second day trip, we booked the @headout southern tour, including both of these GORGEOUS waterfalls and also the black beach, and a stop at the North America/Europe tectonic plates.

What a country!

Luxury on a budget. 4 days in Slovakia and Austria for about $100 a day budget!

I wanted to take my mum and Jaa to 2 new countries for both of them, without breaking the bank, so here's a quick breakdown of how to do that for $100 per day:

WHERE? Bratislava and Vienna

HOW? Ryanair and Wizz Air both fly from around Europe for about $30!

SCHEDULE:
We need 4 nights/3 days. So our schedule was like this:

DAY 1 - Arrive: 
Arrive on an evening fligth to Bratislava, $6 uber to hotel. Free glass of Prosecco when you check in to the @hoteldevin so we had that (and then another!) before hitting the sack. 

DAY 2 - Bratislava
Lazy morning. Then we took a river cruise on the Danube with Lod.Sk. They run all day, we took the 10.30am. 
After that, you disembark RIGHT at a river-beach bar, so Aperol Spritz it was!
Then a DIY walking tour of the beautiful Bratislava old town. Late lunch in the old town square. And dinner on the Hviezdoslavovo námestie boulevard.

DAY 3 - Vienna, Austria Day trip/
Vienna is one of the most beautiful cities in the world, but also the most expensive. So if you wanna see it, base yourself in Bratislava and take a gorgeous boat ride (90 mins, $50 return) there and back. In Vienna then, do a DIY walking tour but make sure not to miss the home of the Sachertorte too. Delicious. Then boat back to Bratislava for dinner.

DAY 4 - Castles, views and sunset in Slovakia. 
Spend the day at both Devin Castle and the icon of Bratislava, Bratislava castle.
Then late afternoon, go up the UFO tower for epic city views. 
Finish with dinner and drinks in the beautiful riverside by the Eurovea Embankment. Heaven.

DAY 5 - home/onwards!
My mum on her $30 flight back to the UK. Jaa and I on the 5 hour train to Prague. 

TOTAL BUDGET?
$450 per person for 4 days. That is what you call luxury on a budget!

Wrapping up my post-Everest celebrations, and some tips for you guys for Prague, Czech Republic!

HOW WE GOT THERE: I took a train from Bratislava, Slovakia. And for an extra €40 I upgraded us to first class. Highly recommended, complete with champagne and olives 🥂 

HOW LONG TO STAY? We did 3 days and 4 nights. It’s my 3rd time in Prague, and I think that this is the sweet spot tbh.

WHERE TO STAY? If you’re on a boozy boys trip, stay somewhere cheap. If you’re on a romantic break, I’d suggest @alchymist_hotel and Spa, Praha Czech. The building is over 500 years old, booking.com score over 9, the most beautiful architecture and the right energy and architecture for Prague. Rooms start around $200. Insane value for such a luxury place.

SIMPLE ITINERARY:
Day 1: Old City stuff
Begin at Prague Castle for stunning views. Explore St. Vitus Cathedral, Golden Lane, and Charles Bridge. Discover Old Town Square's Astronomical Clock.

Day 2: Art and Unique Experiences
Visit the National Gallery and Jewish Quarter. Experience Wenceslas Square and shop. DO NOT MISS the @originalbeerspa , soaking in hops and barley goodness. It was a really highlight of my trip! Enjoy an evening river cruise.

Day 3: Local Flavors and Nightlife
Morning at Vyšehrad Castle. Savor a Czech lunch in Vinohrady. Explore Letná Park and the metronome. Visit an absinthe bar for a taste of the iconic green spirit. Enjoy Žižkov's vibrant nightlife.

BUDGET? 
On a boozy boys low-end trip last time, I spent $100 a day.
This time on a high-end luxury trip with my mrs, it was $150 a day each or so. 

TLDR? When in Prague stay at a boutique hotel (not a chain), don’t miss the beer spa, wander the old city. Maximise the experience by using the train to visit nearby countries (for us we did Bratislava, Slovakia and Vienna, Austria).

The Gates of Hell, Turkmenistan

🇹🇲 A tough country to visit, a tricky visa, but home to one of the coolest attractions in the world - the gates of hell!

⛺️20 of us pitched our tents beside this place, swapped stories, drank whiskey and had a pretty epic time

🌎 I first visited back in 2016 and have been dying to run a OneStep4Ward trip here for years, but it was the last country in the world to open from Covid. The day it opened, we made it happen!

💚 There’s a lot more to Turkmenistan than just this, I’ll share more pics tomorrow.

✈️ I’m back in 3 weeks with another group and cannot wait. Special, special place.

The other side of traveling in Turkmenistan. The Gates of Hell are the highlight but the rest of it was pretty epic too!

🇹🇲Turkmenistan is bordered by Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Iran and Kacakhstan as well as the Caspian Sea. It’s a country that few visit, and that’s a shame. Really fun place to travel around. And to see then leave the Soviet Union and then to create a very ‘unique’ country is fascinating. A brilliant few days ❤️

ITINERARY:
We did 5 nights. 
Day 1:Arrived in Ashgabat at 3am and spent 2 hours with paperwork to enter 🤮. 

Day 2: Quick morning tour of the crazy marble buildings in Ashgabat, then off to the crater where we overnighted, camped, drank, and tried not to fall into the burning crater.

Day 3: Back to the capital, sauna, shower, then off to the train station for an epic overnight Soviet sleeper train, 14 hours and 650km across the country.

Day 4: Arrive at the Caspian Sea, and road trip to the spectacular Yangy Kala canyon. Then a little tour of Turkmenibashi. Gatecrashed a birthday for dinner.

Day 5: fly back to the capital. Check out the UNESCO Nisa fortress, and visit the famous Turkmen horses. Free time to either chill, shop, or check out more epic monuments in the capital. Dinner and drinks at the 6* rooftop restaurant to sign off.

Day 6: awful 3am departure and I’m off home. Chiang Mai is calling!
I’m building my mum a house in Thailand for $150k ❤️🇹🇭

I turned 40 yesterday. And I do it with gratitude, with no negative attachments to getting older. Equally, I don’t have it all figured out, and mostly I make it up as I go along but it’s going ok for me so far. 
A few things have helped along the way, so for anyone hoping to follow my footsteps, make a little money online, travel a bit, challenge themselves, even donate a chunk of cash here and there, here are a few things that helped turn me from a skinny-fat 30yo party boy to a content 40yo, probably more helpful for young guys than girls, but here we are: 
NOTE: Lots of this may be jarring. Sorry not sorry. I believe that a full life, and a fulfilled life, one where you fulfil your potential, requires suffering. And it’s all worth it in the end. I HATE fluffy woke nonsense - “do your best”, “don’t push yourself too hard”. Life is hard, and that’s ok. The beauty is in the struggle. So, 20 lessons that changed my life:

BLOG POST LINK IN BIO but short answer is: 
1) DAILY STACK. Take your daily multi-vitamins.
2) PROTEIN. Get your protein in.
3) I keep an ALKALINE DIET. 
4) I TRACK MY ALCOHOL. 
5) FAST. I fast regularly.
6) DON’T GO 3 DAYS WITHOUT REAL EXERCISE.
7) BIG MUSCLES DON’T EQUAL FITNESS or health.
8) SET GOALS. And write them down.
9) TRACK YOUR WEIGHT and body fat %.
10) I TRACK MY NET WORTH WEEKLY.
11) INVEST. Pay your investments first each month.
12) MAKE AN EFFORT WITH PEOPLE YOU LOVE. 
13) BE LEGIT AMBITIOUS. 
14) “ADDING 1kg PER YEAR MAKES YOUR OLD”.
15) SPEND TIME WITH YOUR PARENTS. 
16) EMBRACE STOICISM. 
17) MAKE YOUR MONEY ONLINE.
18) TRAVEL AND ADVENTURE. 
19) YOU’RE NEVER AS YOUNG AS YOU ARE TONIGHT.
20) BACK DOWN.

In the meantime though, to complete the 7 summits is a dream come true. Historically, these kinda things were done by a very select section of society. I hope this guy doing it can show everyone else that it doesn’t matter about where you come from, it only matters where you’re going. Thanks everyone for the support. We did it ❤️☘️

Antarctica Marathon ✅

I had a day off between my Mount Vinson expedition, and my trip to the South Pole. I promised myself if I found the time, I’d try to run a marathon in Antarctica, so here we go.

Freezing, uncomfortable and a pretty awful idea 😂 Living on a mountain for the 8 days prior wasn’t exactly good preparation but I got it done. There is an Antartica marathon event yearly and it’s $25k+, so I figured I’d do one solo and avoid having to come back and pay that! Limping around like a broken man today.

Weather looking good so fingers crossed for South Pole trip asap!

IM AT THE SOUTH POLE. An emotional day to be honest. And a huge, huge goal complete for me. Time to start a family and focus on that, and on business, for a while perhaps ❤️

And with that I’ve become the first person in history to officially complete the ULTIMATE EXPLORERS GRAND SLAM 🌍 🌎 🌏 

✅ Every country in the world. That’s the 197 officially countries, PLUS all the observer states and land masses (Somaliland and Somalia, Greenland etc)

🏔️ The 7 summits. The highest mountain on every continent, plus the 2 secondary ambiguous mountains (Mont Blanc, and Mount Kosciusko)

📍 Reach both the North and South Pole

Coming for 16 days to Antartica has been the coldest, most expensive expedition of my life. I’ve got what I came for, Mount Vinson summit, Antartica marathon and now reaching the South Pole. It’s time to go home. Counting the days 🇹🇭❤️☘️
